  "diary": "Started the day watering my plants—the monstera's looking especially green this morning. The drive to Station 28 was smooth, caught the tail end of the sunrise over the Sound. Shift began with the usual checks and drills. We had a handful of calls scattered through the afternoon, nothing too serious, which felt like a gift on such a beautiful day. The crew made a decent lasagna for lunch, and we traded the usual jokes. Around dinner I heard folks talking about the World Cup match, and honestly, I was curious. Caught the highlights later with some of the younger guys—good energy in the station, even though we were all tired by then. The day felt right, you know? Honest work, solid people, and that rare Monday where everything just moves at the right pace.",
  "thought_process": "I chose to lean into the routine today because after 57 years and decades on the job, that's what grounds me. The weather was beautiful but didn't really pull at me—I'm used to watching Seattle from inside the station. I did notice the World Cup buzz and decided to engage with it during wind-down because the crew needed it, and honestly, so did I. The light rail closure didn't matter since I drive to Interbay anyway. My mood stayed steady all day; no major calls meant I could settle into the rhythm of maintenance and camaraderie. By evening I felt that familiar satisfaction—tired but purposeful. The plants at home felt like a small anchor before the shift, and knowing they'd still be there waiting made the long day feel contained.",
